    "nutrient": "Iron (Fe)",
    "mechanism": "Iron is required for hemoglobin/myoglobin to transport oxygen and for mitochondrial energy and immune function. Non-heme iron absorption is enhanced by gastric acidity and vitamin C and inhibited by calcium, tea/coffee polyphenols, and phytates.",
    "supplement": "Elemental iron as ferrous bisglycinate (gentler on GI) or ferrous sulfate; take with 250–500 mg vitamin C. Dietary boosts: heme iron (red meat, clams/oysters), or legumes, tofu/tempeh, pumpkin seeds, fortified cereals; pair plant sources with vitamin C; avoid tea/coffee and calcium around iron-rich meals; cooking in cast iron can modestly increase iron.",
    "dosage": "If not anemic: 18–27 mg elemental iron daily with food or 40–60 mg elemental iron every other morning on an empty stomach for 8–12 weeks, then reassess ferritin/hemoglobin. Example: ferrous bisglycinate 25 mg elemental daily; or ferrous sulfate 325 mg (≈65 mg elemental) taken every other day if ferritin is known low and tolerated.",
    "caveats": "Do not use if you have hemochromatosis or unexplained high ferritin. Common side effects: nausea, constipation, dark stools—reduce by switching to bisglycinate or using alternate-day dosing. Separate iron by 2+ hours from calcium, antacids/PPIs, tea/coffee, high-fiber bran, and medications like levothyroxine, tetracyclines, or fluoroquinolones. Recheck iron studies (ferritin, CBC) after 8–12 weeks; continue 1–3 months after normalization to replenish stores. Keep supplements out of reach of children (overdose risk)."
