    "nutrient": "Vitamin D (D2 + D3)",
    "mechanism": "Vitamin D increases intestinal calcium/phosphate absorption and supports bone, muscle, and immune function. D3 (cholecalciferol) raises 25(OH)D more effectively than D2.",
    "supplement": "Vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol) softgel or liquid with a meal containing fat. Dietary sources: fatty fish (salmon, sardines), egg yolks, fortified dairy/plant milks, UV-exposed mushrooms. Sunlight: brief midday sun exposure to forearms/legs a few times weekly as season/skin type allows.",
    "dosage": "1,000–2,000 IU (25–50 mcg) D3 daily for 8–12 weeks, then recheck 25(OH)D and adjust to maintain ~30–50 ng/mL (75–125 nmol/L). If limited sun or higher needs, many adults require ~2,000 IU daily; higher therapeutic dosing should be clinician-guided.",
    "caveats": "Upper intake without supervision is generally 4,000 IU (100 mcg)/day. Take with fat for better absorption. Caution with conditions causing hypercalcemia (e.g., hyperparathyroidism, sarcoidosis) or with thiazide diuretics; monitor calcium if at risk of kidney stones. Consider ensuring adequate magnesium and dietary calcium to support vitamin D metabolism. Reassess levels after 8–12 weeks; adjust seasonally."
